The College Preparation Intervention Program may include activities to:
Improve diagnosis of basic skill deficiencies of middle and high school students to enhance the preparedness of the students for college;
Establish a testing program, using presently administered tests to the extent possible, to evaluate achievement levels and assess the preparation of high school students who are potentially college bound;
Compile a list of courses of study recommended for college preparation and distribute copies of the list to the high school students and their parents;
Provide information regarding college preparation to high school students in a timely manner so the student can make course changes to be better prepared for college;
Improve information to high schools and local school systems concerning the performance of their graduates at the college level in at least the following areas:
The adequacy of preparation of the students in basic skills on the students' entry into college;
The campus enrollment and transfer patterns of students;
The program choices of the students;
The performance of the students on achievement tests; and
The rate of retention and graduation of students; and
Assist high schools and local school systems in the use of this information to improve student outcomes.
